export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "s22-1", "html": "<p>One thesis has carried this report: in the high-value hard materials, simulation error — not data, interest, or capital — is the binding constraint on discovery, and it is measured, systematic, and fixable by demonstrated means. Three numbers carry it. First, the bias: across 574 DFT-NEB migration paths, five foundation potentials miss ionic barriers by 0.310–0.349 eV against a ~60 meV floor, two of them underestimating 73–78% of barriers — a one-directional optimism no funnel averages out.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"2\">[2]</sup> Second, the floor: Open Catalyst 2020's builders report ML energy errors plateaued near 0.2 eV for two years — five architecture generations spent against labels that sit at the 0.1 eV target themselves.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup> Third, the missing validation: the fusion-relevant steel database ends near 20 dpa against the 50-dpa blanket a DEMO reactor needs — one industry synthesis frames the gap as a &quot;20 dpa wall&quot;; the design figures beneath are EUROfusion's own.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"6\">[6]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"7\">[7]</sup> A biased slope, an inherited floor, an absent qualification chain: three failure shapes, one conclusion. What is measured can be assigned, priced, and killed — each of these errors already has a demonstrated fix with a before-and-after number.</p>\n<p>The bet is time-boxed. Three conditions coincide as of 2026-07-17, and the coincidence is temporary: fixes demonstrated and public — non-equilibrium pretraining, single-structure fine-tuning, multi-fidelity Δ-learning, GPU-day work for a solo investigator; policy money on both sides of the Pacific paying for outcomes — batteries, magnets, alloys, fusion blankets — while no program funds the error bars its own priorities are gated on; and a trust deficit, earned through corrected and fabricated claims, that makes prospectively validated, third-party-checkable work the field's scarcest currency. My working estimate, defended in Chapter 13, is a three-to-five-year window: the time for published fixes to be absorbed into next-generation training corpora, after which advantage migrates from whoever fixes first to whoever owns proprietary, experiment-anchored data. It will not stay open.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s22-2", "html": "<p>By this report's next freshness date — the re-verification of every figure in it, all statuses here as of 2026-07-17 — I commit to three falsifiable artifacts. A public benchmark presence: a compliant Matbench Discovery submission and an OpenKIM deposit with passing Verification Checks, checkable without trusting me. One prospectively validated candidate: a named compound, single digits, with a stability dossier — hydrolysis, oxidation, operando-reconstruction, ordering-kinetics, competing-polymorph screens, as Chapter 14 defines it — synthesized and characterized by independent partners, published either way. One rung climbed on the compute ladder: from the free tiers to an awarded allocation. Kill criteria attach in writing, as in Chapters 18 and 20: if 90:10 Δ-learning fails to reproduce on my hardest class, the wedge narrows to dataset interventions and the successor chapter says so; if the candidate fails at the furnace, the failure publishes beside the prediction; if no external audit confirms value, the wedge claim is retracted.</p>\n<p>I end where the gate is sharpest: the October 2025 rare-earth export-rule suspension lapses 2026-11-10.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"68\">[68]</sup> The magnet commitment stands as Chapter 15 wrote it, unabridged — a conclusion is held to the same grammar as the work:</p>\n<p><em>Because we have unlocked spin-aware, multi-fidelity magnetic simulation, we will discover NdFeB-class rare-earth-free magnets — Fe<span class=\"math\">$_{16}$</span>N<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>, MnAlC, kinetically unlocked tetrataenite — with such magnets we will be able to build motors and turbines immune to export controls. This impacts people in three ways to improve their world: drivers and factory towns whose EVs and wind power stop pricing in a chokepoint; planners who quit scheduling around a foreign licensing decision; magnet workers competing on physics instead of quotas.</em></p>\n<p>Every chain in this report terminates the same way: not in a model and not in a firm, but in a furnace that either runs or does not — and beyond the furnace, in the people the chain names. Hard materials, honest errors: the materials are physics, the honesty is a choice, and the world built from both is ours — all of ours — to build.</p>\n" },
]
